 fine-looking landmark – we have an institution that's entertained generations of grateful Bradfordians and given us something to chirp about in a city that suffers from civic pride deficiency.</p><p>Despite its Edwardian splendour, the Alhambra was always conceived as a cultural playground for the decent, working people of an industrial town (without a bingo ball in sight). Indeed something of a novelty in 1914 was the fact that the \"cheap seats\" were upholstered in the same way as the dress circle, meaning the masses no longer had to settle for stiff wooden benches whilst enjoying their entertainment. </p><p>A century on, and the venue continues to be a social leveller in a city of countless backgrounds. To observe the Italian-marbled foyer before any performance of the Alhambra’s annual pantomime extravaganza (a tradition started by ‘King of Panto’ Laidler himself in the ‘30s) is to see all of Bradford… wealthy ladies from Ilkley… youth groups from Holme wood… Pakistani families from Girlington… a hardworking city coming together in the way Laidler could only have dreamed of when the theatre’s foundations were laid in 1912. </p><p>But her most importantly of all, the Alhambra is something of a rarity in 21st century Bradford – it’s an attraction. And a very successful one at that. The framed playbills adorning the walls under the Alhambra’s domes are testament to the theatre’s importance in Britain’s golden age of variety. Laurel &amp; Hardy, George Formby, Morecambe &amp; Wise - they all considered Bradford an important pin on the map. Today, bums are on seats to see prestigious West End productions, National Theatre plays or the latest Matthew Bourne masterpiece come to town. Sadler’s Wells is little more than a secondary school auditorium once you’ve seen Swan Lake performed under the Alhambra’s ornate plasterwork. </p><p>As the curtain goes up on the Alhambra’s latest coup – the world-renowned production of The Lion King – a new generation of Bradfordians will be mesmerised by what’s happening in their own town, and will hopefully grow to realise what a truly special place it is. Sharing a frontage with the National Media Museum and a potential new music venue in the old Art Deco Odeon building next door, let’s hope the theatre’s continued success acts a catalyst for a resurgence of the arts in a city that desperately needs it. </p><p>Happy Birthday, our Alhambra. You’re Bradford’s past, present, and<i> </i>future.</p><p><b>Follow Si Cunningham on Twitter: @sicunninghamz</b>  </p>","headline":"Happy 100th birthday to Bradford's Alhambra","trailText":"Conceived as a cultural playground for the decent, working people, the startling Alhambra has never been more important for a city on the brink of\na cultural resurgence, argues <b>Si Cunningham</b>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395761754515/8158896880_6c19e03412_o-140x84.jpeg","wordcount":"497","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-29T08:00:20Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2014/mar/26/happy-100th-birthday-to-bradfords-alhambra","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/the-northerner/2014/mar/26/happy-100th-birthday-to-bradfords-alhambra","tags":[{"id":"uk/the-northerner","webTitle":"The Northerner","type":"blog","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/the-northerner","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk/the-northerner","references":[]},{"id":"uk/bradford","webTitle":"Bradford","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/bradford","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk/bradford","references":[]},{"id":"uk/uk","webTitle":"UK news","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/uk","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk/uk","references":[]},{"id":"stage/theatre","webT