 mail route control panel, circa 1935. At its peak the railway conveyed 4 million letters a day, 22 hours a day, along 23 miles of track.\" width=\"620\" height=\"470\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A postman operates an underground mail route control panel in about 1935. By the turn of the 20th century, congested streets and fog meant that mail transported between the main Post Offices and railway stations in London was severely delayed. In February 1911 a departmental committee recommended construction of an electric railway with driverless trains to alleviate the problem. In 1913 the Post Office (London) Railway Act was passed, paving the way for a new railway – six and a half miles long, with tunnels an average of 20 metres (70ft) below ground. It would connect the West End and East End via eight stations. Photograph: courtesy of BPMA</figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-ec70e964-838d-4a2d-94e1-d0a4f805ca78\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395746374256/d7c3a7dc-78bb-4c04-bbb2-f7d9b2798bc8-620x453.jpeg\" alt=\"A car depot and workshop, circa 1932. Tunnelling work was completed in 1917, but the Treasury would not allow the Post Office to order or install the operating equipment during wartime. The high price of materials after the War meant that work on the railway did not resume until 1923. The railway was finally opened on 5 December 1927.\" width=\"620\" height=\"453\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A car depot and workshop in about 1932. Tunnelling work was completed in 1917, but the Treasury would not allow the Post Office to order or install the operating equipment during wartime. The high price of materials after the war meant work on the railway did not resume until 1923. It finally opened on 5 December 1927. Photograph: courtesy of BPMA</figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-23f53312-f13c-4f2a-af5c-ebbb83f18078\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395746492438/856855b0-492e-40aa-9ebb-f37e8295c668-620x462.jpeg\" alt=\"A worker loads mail onto a conveyor belt. The trains run in a single tunnel, 9ft in diameter, with a double 2ft gauge track. At the station approaches, the main tunnel divides into two 7ft tunnels, each with a single track. Although the trains are much smaller than on London's passenger underground, the stations look much the same, with grand circular walls and the familiar sound of approaching trains. The tunnels were used during the First World War to store and protect art treasures belonging to the National Portrait Gallery and the Tate Gallery.\" width=\"620\" height=\"462\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A worker loads mail on to a conveyor belt. The trains ran in a single tunnel, about three metres (9ft) in diameter, with a double 60cm (2ft) gauge track. At the station approaches, the main tunnel divides into two two-metre (7ft) tunnels, each with a single track. Although the trains were much smaller than on London's passenger underground, the stations look much the same, with grand circular walls. The tunnels were used during the first world war to store and protect art treasures belonging to the National Portrait Gallery and the Tate Gallery. Photograph: courtesy of BPMA</figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-2873a8bd-c579-4d43-a132-3fedfe9cd21b\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395747858210/c702c14d-3667-4e0b-8e1e-bd3f65facf49-620x463.jpeg\" alt=\"Mail Rail train in a tunnel. New trains were introduced in 1930, with each 27-foot long single-car train able to carry four mail bag containers. Every container held an average 15 bags of letters or six bags of parcels. Replacement trains were trialled in the 1960s and a new fleet introduced in 1980.\" width=\"620\" height=\"463\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A Mail Rail train in a tunnel. New trains were introduced in 1930, with each eight-metre-long (27ft) single-car train able to carry four mail bag containers. Every container held an average of 15 bags of letters or six bags of parcels. A trial of replacement trains took place in the 1960s and a new fleet was introduced in 1980. Photograph: courtesy of BPMA</figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-7fd1a8e5-4116-4196-ae3e-49a1b484c31d\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395748152576/0267e9c5-ea99-4034-8998-2d9c7665dc59-620x412.jpeg\" alt=\"A mail train sits dormant in a tunnel. To mark its 60th anniversary in 1987, the Post Office Underground Railway changed its name to 'Mail Rail'. Through declining use and closure of the above ground offices the system eventually became un-economical to run. In 2003 the system was suspended and today remains closed.\" width=\"620\" height=\"412\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>A mail train sits dormant in a tunnel. To mark its 60th anniversary in 1987, the Post Office underground railway changed its name to Mail Rail. As its use declined and above-ground offices were closed, the system became un-economical. In 2003 the system was suspended and it remains closed. Photograph: Bradley Photography</figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-a7cf0886-520f-4ab0-96bf-71f8eba146ac\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395748248728/027511c1-ceed-4840-8779-c136476806c5-620x412.jpeg\" alt=\"Descent to Mount Pleasant. As part of a £22m scheme to deliver a new, national postal museum in Central London, the British Postal Museum & Archive is planning on opening up a section of Mail Rail to the general public for the first time in its history.\" width=\"620\" height=\"412\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The descent to Mount Pleasant. As part of a £22m plan for a national postal museum in central London, the British Postal Museum &amp; Archive is to open a section of Mail Rail to the public for the first time in its history. Photograph: Bradley Photography</figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-44bdcef3-3450-4f34-b0a0-160ecae89b79\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395748454429/5816f77c-7369-438c-8b97-d545d05c2999-620x438.jpeg\" alt=\"The depot at Mount Pleasant, where the engines and cars from across the network were brought for maintenance will be transformed into exhibition and corporate hire space, preserving the industrial appearance of the site. Provided all funding can be secured, we envisage that this phase will open at the same time as The Postal Museum itself at Calthorpe House.\" width=\"620\" height=\"438\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>The depot at Mount Pleasant, where engines and cars from across the network were brought for maintenance, will be turned into an exhibition and corporate hire space, with its industrial appearance preserved. Provided all funding can be secured, this phase will open at the same time as the Postal Museum at Calthorpe House. Photograph: courtesy of BPMA</figcaption> </figure>  <figure class=\"element element-image\" data-media-id=\"gu-fc-c12c7bcd-4a9a-4828-928c-cc960b71f6fc\"> <img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/25/1395748523373/86cbd373-cb30-481d-83f5-e6b30c6c4998-620x438.jpeg\" alt=\"Under a second phase, expected to open a few years later in 2019, visitors will be able to take a ride on replica trains along a 1km loop of track through Mount Pleasant station.\" width=\"620\" height=\"438\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption>In a second phase, expected to open a few years later in 2019, visitors will be able to take a ride on replica trains along a 1km loop of track through Mount Pleasant station. Photograph: courtesy of BPMA</figcaption> </fi