rty-london","fields":{"standfirst":"The London mayor has applauded the budget's pension reforms for creating new property investment opportunities, but not everybody shares his glee","hasStoryPackage":"false","body":"<figure data-media-id='gu-image-432940448'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2012/2/22/1329931931486/London-property-for-sale-007.jpg' alt='London property for sale' width='460' height='276' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Signs of London's booming housing market. Photograph: Daniel Berehulak/Getty Images</figcaption></figure><p>The most interesting part of Boris Johnson's <a href=\"http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/pensions/10717846/Budget-2014-the-Lamborghini-ride-that-says-power-to-the-people.html\">Monday morning praise </a>for George Osborne's <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2014/mar/22/death-compulsory-annuities-pension-revolution\">dramatic pension fund reforms</a> came near the end, when his red-baiting, pre-election rhetoric gave way to a prediction: now that people will be allowed to take larger lumps from the pot of money they've saved for their old age, most won't blow the lot on Italian sports cars but sink it into bricks and mortar:</p><blockquote><p><br />I think the vast majority will want to put their pots into the market with the greatest yield over the past 40 years – and that is property; and I expect huge numbers of those approaching pensionable age will be thinking about how they – the baby boomers – can do something to help the younger generation with the single biggest problem they face, namely the cost of housing...</p><p>It is a chance for the older generation to find that sudden wodge of dosh that will enable them to help their children or grandchildren find a deposit and get on the [housing] ladder; and the existence of those new deposits will give developers even greater confidence to build more homes – and faster than they are now.</p></blockquote><p>Not everyone was quite as joyful, though. <a href=\"http://www.economist.com/blogs/blighty/2014/03/house-prices-and-pension-pots?fsrc=scn/tw_ec/build_on_the_green_belt_or_introduce_space_rationing_your_choice\">The Economist</a>, for instance:</p><blockquote><p>No member of the cabinet will say this, but Boris is quite right: one consequence of this reform is likely to be yet more money flooding into Britain's overheated housing market. There will be two flows. First, as Boris approvingly suggests, retiring baby boomers will lend their children money to put together a deposit for a house. Second, as he skips over, they will use the money as a deposit of their own to buy flats or houses to be rented out...</p><p>The trouble is, the consequences will not be as benign as the Mayor seems to think. Because housing isn't quite like other goods. Look at it like this: if lots more people put down deposits on new cars, car manufacturers will simply expand supply. Since car-making is highly competitive, and the supply of raw materials fairly easily increased, all that extra demand will not have much effect on the price. </p><p>With housing, by contrast, the supply is almost wholly unresponsive to price. If you increase the number of people who can afford to buy homes at current prices, then the main effect will be to raise prices high again to make housing about as unaffordable as it was before.</p></blockquote><p>So much, yet again, for Mayor Johnson's big bubble of total faith in the self-correcting urge of market forces - especially where housing is concerned. And yet, as the Economist says, his hunch about baby-boomers may well be right. Property prices in London are now so utterly extreme that even people like me - good job, a bit put by, long-term owner-occupier - shudder at the price tags on local two-bedroom flats, and this in a neighbourhood which, though suddenly <a href=\"http://davehill.typepad.com/claptonian/gentrification/\">gentrifying at spectacular speed</a>, is still very far from being the capital's priciest. </p><p>What hope do the children of even London parents in my sort of position have of avoiding the capital's (also too expensive) private rented sector and buying somewhere vaguely near where they grew up, let alone all those who are much worse off? Unless they strike it very rich, the hopes of many of them are already pretty small - and may well indeed end up depending on mum and dad tipping out their pension pots. So, well spotted, Mr Mayor. But how grateful for this whole, desperate state of affairs do you expect us be?</p>","headline":"London housing crisis: Boris's bubble of belief","trailText":"<p>The London mayor has applauded the budget's pension reforms for creating new property investment opportunities, but not everybody shares his glee</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/3nzd7","wordcount":"590","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-04-01T11:22:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/davehillblog/2014/mar/25/boris-johnson-budget-pension-property-london","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/davehillblog/2014/mar/25/boris-johnson-budget-pension-property-london","tags":[{"id":"uk/davehillblog","webTitle":"Dave Hill's London blog","type":"blog","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk/davehillblog","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk/davehillblog","references":[]},{"id":"politics/boris","webTitle":"Boris Johnson","type":"keyword","sectionId":"politics","sectionName":"Politics","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/boris","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/politics/boris","references":[]},{"id":"tone/blog","webTitle":"Blogposts","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/blog","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/tone/blog","references":[]},{"id":"profile/davehill","webTitle":"Dave Hill","rcsId":"GNL064289","r2ContributorId":"21999","bylineImageUrl":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-image